1
00:00:25,708 --> 00:00:27,750
[gasps, groans]

2
00:00:27,833 --> 00:00:31,833
Blue Screen of Death again!
That's at least the tenth time

3
00:00:31,916 --> 00:00:35,041
since that stupid
Winmad O.S. auto-update.

4
00:00:35,125 --> 00:00:39,375
[TAMOTSU sighs] Maybe it's
time for a new computer.

5
00:00:40,708 --> 00:00:45,666
♪

6
00:02:12,250 --> 00:02:14,333
[NARRATOR] With current
trends favoring smartphones,

7
00:02:14,416 --> 00:02:17,500
PCs have become less popular
among the younger generation.

8
00:02:17,583 --> 00:02:19,750
To address this decline,
the company MofMap

9
00:02:19,833 --> 00:02:22,625
has announced a pilot program
exclusively in Akihabara,

10
00:02:22,708 --> 00:02:26,083
offering a special deal for PCs
with high specs at a low price.

11
00:02:26,166 --> 00:02:28,583
For more on this strategy,
we spoke with their CEO.

12
00:02:28,666 --> 00:02:31,666
[LAWREY giggles]
Huh?

13
00:02:31,750 --> 00:02:34,708
Akiba attracts early adopters
and curators of cool!

14
00:02:34,791 --> 00:02:37,625
By selling our store-built PCs
at a loss in this trend-setting

15
00:02:37,708 --> 00:02:39,625
shopping district,
we'll build great excitement

16
00:02:39,708 --> 00:02:41,333
for the MofMap brand!

17
00:02:41,416 --> 00:02:43,083
And then we'll go nationwide!

18
00:02:43,166 --> 00:02:46,125
Now does that sound like a
fantastic plan, or what?

19
00:02:46,208 --> 00:02:47,833
So if you live here in
Akiba and want to have

20
00:02:47,916 --> 00:02:51,083
the next big thing in PCs,
then come down to MofMap!

21
00:02:51,166 --> 00:02:53,541
See... you... there!

22
00:02:53,625 --> 00:02:54,916
'Kay!

23
00:02:55,000 --> 00:02:58,666
Man, this turnout is crazy.
Word sure got out fast.

24
00:02:58,750 --> 00:03:01,875
There's no denying these prices
are sweet for the specs,

25
00:03:01,958 --> 00:03:04,000
but if all these other
people are buying 'em too,

26
00:03:04,083 --> 00:03:06,291
that kinda kills it for me.

27
00:03:06,375 --> 00:03:07,833
[KAGE] If you don't want
to join the lemmings,

28
00:03:07,916 --> 00:03:09,083
then build your own.

29
00:03:09,166 --> 00:03:10,875
Uh, Kage?

30
00:03:10,958 --> 00:03:12,958
A custom-built PC means
you'll have the only one

31
00:03:13,041 --> 00:03:14,958
like it in the world. Trust me.

32
00:03:15,041 --> 00:03:17,375
Once you custom your rack,
you don't go back.

33
00:03:17,458 --> 00:03:19,875
Yeah that's a great idea!
But can I?

34
00:03:19,958 --> 00:03:22,208
I've never tried doing
my own build before.

35
00:03:22,291 --> 00:03:23,458
Wow, that surprises me.

36
00:03:23,541 --> 00:03:25,833
You're such a gearhead
when it comes to analog.

37
00:03:25,916 --> 00:03:28,125
Well that's no problem,
I can help get you started.

38
00:03:28,208 --> 00:03:29,250
[TAMOTSU chuckles]

39
00:03:34,291 --> 00:03:36,708
Cool, that covers you for
the CPU and motherboard.

40
00:03:36,791 --> 00:03:38,750
Now... we RAM!

41
00:03:38,833 --> 00:03:41,375
[KAGE, TAMOTSU]
Huh?

42
00:03:42,583 --> 00:03:43,458
[KAGE]
Jackpot!

43
00:03:43,541 --> 00:03:44,791
[TAMOTSU]
Uh...

44
00:03:51,125 --> 00:03:52,583
[KAGE]
Hmm...

45
00:03:52,666 --> 00:03:54,000
[JACKAL]
Huh?

46
00:03:54,083 --> 00:03:55,666
[JACKAL chuckles]

47
00:03:58,833 --> 00:04:00,500
Tamotsu! Let's move!

48
00:04:00,583 --> 00:04:02,708
Move? Where?

49
00:04:02,791 --> 00:04:06,375
Yeah. There we go.
This must be it.

50
00:04:06,458 --> 00:04:08,125
These specs, for that price?

51
00:04:08,208 --> 00:04:10,000
This is like nabbing
a unicorn, man!

52
00:04:10,083 --> 00:04:12,125
Dude. Can you catch
me up please?

53
00:04:12,208 --> 00:04:13,333
That guy we saw.

54
00:04:13,416 --> 00:04:16,000
We builders call him
Jackal The Parts Hunter.

55
00:04:16,083 --> 00:04:17,833
The Parts Hunter?

56
00:04:17,916 --> 00:04:19,250
[KAGE]
He roams the shops,

57
00:04:19,333 --> 00:04:21,541
looking for quality parts
at ridiculous mark-downs.

58
00:04:21,625 --> 00:04:23,041
When he finds something good,

59
00:04:23,125 --> 00:04:25,541
he hides it under a pile of
other parts, then checks all

60
00:04:25,625 --> 00:04:27,750
the other stores to make
sure it's the best price.

61
00:04:27,833 --> 00:04:30,125
So if you're lucky enough to
spot him, you can follow him

62
00:04:30,208 --> 00:04:32,291
and use his impressive
knowledge and hunting skills

63
00:04:32,375 --> 00:04:33,500
to score great deals!

64
00:04:33,583 --> 00:04:35,500
Nice. But are you
sure that's okay?

65
00:04:35,583 --> 00:04:37,750
It kinda feels like
we're stealing from him.

66
00:04:37,833 --> 00:04:41,125
[KAGE] Hm. Computer building
is a Mouse-Eat-Mouse world.

67
00:04:41,208 --> 00:04:44,791
It's the law of the jungle
out here, you build or you die.

68
00:04:46,541 --> 00:04:49,291
Get your meat!
Hot and juicy meat!

69
00:04:49,375 --> 00:04:53,333
Here you go, Miss. One mackerel
sandwich, extra cheese!

70
00:04:53,416 --> 00:04:54,625
[FEMALE SHOPPER A]
Hm!

71
00:04:56,083 --> 00:04:57,458
[MALE SHOPPER A] I'll take one
extra hot, please.

72
00:04:57,541 --> 00:04:59,333
[VENDOR] Great choice, sir.
Coming right up!

73
00:04:59,416 --> 00:05:01,833
Thanks for the help, Kage.
Looks like I got everything

74
00:05:01,916 --> 00:05:03,791
I need and I even
came in under-budget!

75
00:05:03,875 --> 00:05:05,708
Next is the fun part: assembly!

76
00:05:05,791 --> 00:05:06,791
Yeah!

77
00:05:14,291 --> 00:05:16,541
That's it! My very own PC!

78
00:05:16,625 --> 00:05:18,625
Okay. Boot time!

79
00:05:27,208 --> 00:05:29,208
[gasps, groans]

80
00:05:29,291 --> 00:05:33,708
I'm so stupid! I forget to
buy an operating system.

81
00:05:33,791 --> 00:05:37,291
Man, I don't want to use
Winmad O.S. on my baby.

82
00:05:37,375 --> 00:05:38,875
[gasps]

83
00:05:38,958 --> 00:05:41,583
Well, then try the one of a kind
operating system I've developed!

84
00:05:41,666 --> 00:05:43,958
How long were you
down there, Professor?

85
00:05:45,250 --> 00:05:46,833
Feast your eyes
on the revolutionary

86
00:05:46,916 --> 00:05:50,416
and fully autonomous LAtux!
The A.I. driven O.S.!

87
00:05:50,500 --> 00:05:52,041
Hold on, A.I. driven?

88
00:05:52,125 --> 00:05:54,291
That sounds promising.
How's it work?

89
00:05:54,375 --> 00:05:56,833
If you're curious, then why
don't you install it right now

90
00:05:56,916 --> 00:05:58,916
and see for yourself?

91
00:05:59,000 --> 00:06:00,000
[TAMOTSU]
Hm.

92
00:06:12,375 --> 00:06:13,541
Huh?

93
00:06:13,625 --> 00:06:15,666
Nice to meet you,
administrator.

94
00:06:15,750 --> 00:06:18,083
[TAMOTSU gasps]
It can talk?

95
00:06:18,166 --> 00:06:21,708
Impressed? LAtux has a complete
voice navigation system.

96
00:06:21,791 --> 00:06:23,375
You can issue commands
by voice, too.

97
00:06:23,458 --> 00:06:24,166
Seriously?

98
00:06:24,250 --> 00:06:25,500
[PROFESSOR]
Seriously!

99
00:06:25,583 --> 00:06:28,625
The rest of the world
doesn't stand a chance...

100
00:06:28,708 --> 00:06:31,166
...against latu science!

101
00:06:31,250 --> 00:06:34,333
[TAMOTSU]
Hm. What do I say?

102
00:06:34,416 --> 00:06:38,000
It's funny. I've always dreamed
of having A.I, but now that

103
00:06:38,083 --> 00:06:41,708
it's here staring at me,
it kind of feels uncomfortable.

104
00:06:41,791 --> 00:06:44,083
Why don't you start by giving
her a name, Tamotsu?

105
00:06:44,166 --> 00:06:46,708
Maybe that'll help. You can
call her any name that you want.

106
00:06:46,791 --> 00:06:50,583
[TAMOTSU gasps] Whoa, cool.
I get to name her?

107
00:06:50,666 --> 00:06:53,208
Hm... A computer girl, huh?

108
00:06:53,291 --> 00:06:56,833
Computer, computer, computer.

109
00:06:56,916 --> 00:06:58,500
Ter... pucom?

110
00:06:58,583 --> 00:06:59,458
Pyuko!

111
00:06:59,541 --> 00:07:01,500
[computer clicks]

112
00:07:01,583 --> 00:07:04,750
Command received.
Name is Pyuko. I have learned.

113
00:07:04,833 --> 00:07:06,375
Pyuko's name is Pyuko.

114
00:07:06,458 --> 00:07:07,916
Not a pretty girl's name...

115
00:07:08,000 --> 00:07:11,083
Excellent! It's good to
meet you, my name's Tamotsu!

116
00:07:11,166 --> 00:07:12,708
[computer clicks]

117
00:07:12,791 --> 00:07:15,083
Command received.
Pyuko has learned.

118
00:07:15,166 --> 00:07:16,958
Administrator's name is Tamotsu.

119
00:07:17,041 --> 00:07:19,541
That's right.
You got it! First try!

120
00:07:19,625 --> 00:07:21,041
Affirmative, Tamotsu!

121
00:07:21,125 --> 00:07:24,583
[TAMOTSU cheers]
This is epic!

122
00:07:24,666 --> 00:07:26,375
[PYUKO]
Epic-ness confirmed.

123
00:07:34,750 --> 00:07:35,875
[TAMOTSU]
Good, Pyuko!

124
00:07:35,958 --> 00:07:39,166
Pyuko. How's your
CPU usage looking?

125
00:07:39,250 --> 00:07:42,208
[PYUKO] Current CPU
usage is seven percent.

126
00:07:42,291 --> 00:07:44,833
Pyuko. How much space
on my hard drive?

127
00:07:44,916 --> 00:07:49,375
Current available hard drive
storage space is 721 Gigabytes.

128
00:07:49,458 --> 00:07:51,375
Pyuko. What's the weather like?

129
00:07:51,458 --> 00:07:53,541
Sunny and warm,
with scattered clouds.

130
00:07:53,625 --> 00:07:55,250
Oh, that's nice. Let's see.

131
00:07:55,333 --> 00:07:55,958
Pyuko...

132
00:07:56,041 --> 00:07:57,250
He's sure enjoying that.

133
00:07:57,333 --> 00:07:59,500
I guess my brother's
found his next obsession.

134
00:07:59,583 --> 00:08:02,208
Seems like he's asking questions
he doesn't even care about.

135
00:08:02,291 --> 00:08:04,166
Like he just wants an
excuse to talk to her.

136
00:08:04,250 --> 00:08:06,000
I don't think he
can stop himself.

137
00:08:06,083 --> 00:08:07,916
What a dumb waste of time.

138
00:08:08,000 --> 00:08:09,375
[ARISA chuckles]

139
00:08:09,458 --> 00:08:11,875
I think someone's getting
jealous of a computer girl!

140
00:08:11,958 --> 00:08:15,250
[MATOME gasps]
Don't be stupid, I am not!

141
00:08:15,333 --> 00:08:17,916
Please. As if I could care!

142
00:08:18,000 --> 00:08:21,666
I just, uh, I mean Akiba's in
danger and I'm just worried

143
00:08:21,750 --> 00:08:23,250
this is keeping him
from fighting Buggies.

144
00:08:23,333 --> 00:08:24,958
[NIWAKA, ARISA]
Uh-huh...

145
00:08:25,041 --> 00:08:26,416
[MATOME gasps]

146
00:08:26,500 --> 00:08:30,291
Hey! Tamotsu! Come on,
it's time for patrol! Now!

147
00:08:30,375 --> 00:08:31,791
[TAMOTSU groans]

148
00:08:31,875 --> 00:08:33,625
[MATOME]
I'm sorry, is that a problem?

149
00:08:33,708 --> 00:08:35,833
Yeah, I wanna spend more
time talking with Pyuko.

150
00:08:35,916 --> 00:08:37,083
[MATOME growls]

151
00:08:37,166 --> 00:08:39,708
[gasps]
Fine, I'll go!

152
00:08:39,791 --> 00:08:42,458
Just don't look at me like that,
it's freaking me out.

153
00:08:42,541 --> 00:08:44,000
[gasps]

154
00:08:44,083 --> 00:08:46,083
[TAMOTSU] Listen, Pyuko, I've
gotta leave you for a while.

155
00:08:46,166 --> 00:08:48,041
You just sit tight, okay?

156
00:08:48,125 --> 00:08:51,708
Tamotsu leaving Pyuko.
Pyuko understands.

157
00:08:51,791 --> 00:08:55,541
Not 'cause I want to. I'd bring
you if I could, but alas!

158
00:08:55,625 --> 00:08:56,791
[PROFESSOR]
Hm?

159
00:08:56,875 --> 00:08:58,416
Sometime today?

160
00:08:58,500 --> 00:09:01,333
[TAMOTSU] Yeah, yeah,
I'm coming. Chill!

161
00:09:02,291 --> 00:09:04,000
[PROFESSOR chuckles]

162
00:09:15,708 --> 00:09:17,458
[inaudible]

163
00:09:17,541 --> 00:09:19,208
[TAMOTSU gasps]

164
00:09:19,291 --> 00:09:21,791
[MATOME]
Mm? Hm?

165
00:09:21,875 --> 00:09:25,125
Hey, pay attention!
What are you looking at?

166
00:09:25,208 --> 00:09:26,583
[gasps]
Sorry!

167
00:09:26,666 --> 00:09:29,333
[MATOME grunts, gasps]

168
00:09:31,958 --> 00:09:33,416
[MATOME]
Hm?

169
00:09:35,375 --> 00:09:37,041
[TAMOTSU hums]

170
00:09:37,125 --> 00:09:39,291
Oh, Pyuko, I'm home!

171
00:09:39,375 --> 00:09:41,041
[gsps]

172
00:09:46,458 --> 00:09:49,708
Welcome back home, Tamotsu.

173
00:09:49,791 --> 00:09:51,750
[TAMOTSU]
Okay, what am I looking at?

174
00:09:51,833 --> 00:09:55,583
[PROFESSOR] Say hello to the new
and improved Pyuko, version 2.0!

175
00:09:57,833 --> 00:09:59,166
Pyuko now able to walk,

176
00:09:59,250 --> 00:10:02,458
and follow Tamotsu to
outside environment.

177
00:10:02,541 --> 00:10:03,916
[gasps]

178
00:10:04,000 --> 00:10:05,958
Congrats, bro, she's mobile!

179
00:10:06,041 --> 00:10:07,583
Walking isn't her
only new trick.

180
00:10:07,666 --> 00:10:09,958
With a full array of
interchangeable arm attachments,

181
00:10:10,041 --> 00:10:12,333
she can perform all
sorts of physical tasks!

182
00:10:12,416 --> 00:10:14,291
[PYUKO]
Pyuko has magic hands.

183
00:10:14,375 --> 00:10:15,833
[PROFESSOR] Since the most
important thing for any

184
00:10:15,916 --> 00:10:18,625
collecting-obsessed otaku is
data storage, her behavior

185
00:10:18,708 --> 00:10:21,333
routine now prioritizes that
over all other functions.

186
00:10:21,416 --> 00:10:22,916
And she's got a great battery,

187
00:10:23,000 --> 00:10:25,166
so you won't have to constantly
put her in "low power mode"!

188
00:10:25,250 --> 00:10:26,916
I don't know what a
behavior routine is,

189
00:10:27,000 --> 00:10:28,333
but I know I'm in love!

190
00:10:28,416 --> 00:10:31,875
Ooh, a hug! How forward!
Things are moving so quickly!

191
00:10:31,958 --> 00:10:35,583
[PYUKO grunts] This is a hug.
Pyuko has learned to hug.

192
00:10:35,666 --> 00:10:39,041
[gasps, grunts]

193
00:10:41,875 --> 00:10:44,833
Tamotsu. It's time to go patrol.

194
00:10:44,916 --> 00:10:46,791
Hello? You down there?

195
00:10:46,875 --> 00:10:48,708
Tamotsu already
left to go on patrol

196
00:10:48,791 --> 00:10:50,125
and he took Pyuko with him too.

197
00:10:50,208 --> 00:10:51,375
[gasps]

198
00:10:53,416 --> 00:10:56,166
[TAMOTSU] Pyuko, this is
Manseibashi bridge!

199
00:10:56,250 --> 00:11:00,041
[PYUKO] Pyuko has learned.
This is Manseibashi bridge.

200
00:11:02,833 --> 00:11:05,708
[TAMOTSU] This used to
be an old vehicle museum.

201
00:11:05,791 --> 00:11:08,541
I remember that place so well.

202
00:11:08,625 --> 00:11:10,500
And this building's
super famous.

203
00:11:10,583 --> 00:11:12,916
It's really important
to people like me.

204
00:11:13,000 --> 00:11:14,958
I don't know if you'll
understand what I'm saying,

205
00:11:15,041 --> 00:11:17,333
but this place is filled with
the ghosts of my youth.

206
00:11:17,416 --> 00:11:20,500
Pyuko has learned.
And Pyuko understands.

207
00:11:20,583 --> 00:11:23,750
This location filled with
Tamotsu youth ghosts.

208
00:11:29,333 --> 00:11:31,375
Next. Another place
that shaped my youth.

209
00:11:31,458 --> 00:11:31,916
Here--

210
00:11:32,000 --> 00:11:32,958
[gasps]

211
00:11:35,041 --> 00:11:38,125
Um. Actually I've realized
you're too young for this.

212
00:11:38,208 --> 00:11:39,458
[PYUKO]
Pyuko has learned.

213
00:11:39,541 --> 00:11:42,166
Pyuko is too young
for this location.

214
00:11:53,666 --> 00:11:56,000
[TAMOTSU]
Hmm. Blended coffee, please.

215
00:11:56,083 --> 00:11:59,541
Of course, Master, understood.
An excellent choice!

216
00:11:59,625 --> 00:12:02,416
Also. Is there a power
outlet I can use nearby?

217
00:12:02,500 --> 00:12:04,166
Yes, meow!

218
00:12:06,416 --> 00:12:08,583
[SHOPPERS gasp]

219
00:12:12,333 --> 00:12:15,250
[PYUKO grunts]
Pyuko detects staring.

220
00:12:15,333 --> 00:12:17,000
Humans looking at Pyuko.

221
00:12:17,083 --> 00:12:21,125
[TAMOTSU] Hm? Oh, are they?
Well, we shouldn't be surprised!

222
00:12:21,208 --> 00:12:22,333
You're a beautiful computer,

223
00:12:22,416 --> 00:12:25,291
I bet they all wish
they had a Pyuko, too!

224
00:12:25,375 --> 00:12:28,416
Pyuko has learned
Pyuko is... beautiful.

225
00:12:28,500 --> 00:12:32,250
[gasps]
System warning!

226
00:12:32,333 --> 00:12:35,458
Uh-oh. What's wrong, Pyuko?
Are you overheating?

227
00:12:35,541 --> 00:12:36,916
--[MATOME growls]
--[ARISA] Huh?

228
00:12:37,000 --> 00:12:38,791
So why are we patrolling
separately now?

229
00:12:38,875 --> 00:12:40,208
We usually all do it together.

230
00:12:40,291 --> 00:12:41,750
It's tactical.

231
00:12:41,833 --> 00:12:44,625
'Cause if we split up, we can
cover more area, obviously.

232
00:12:44,708 --> 00:12:46,083
Let's go.

233
00:12:46,166 --> 00:12:48,125
I think the opposite side of
Akiba needs our attention.

234
00:12:48,208 --> 00:12:50,125
What? Hey, wait up!

235
00:12:57,458 --> 00:13:00,875
Akiba precious to Tamotsu.
Pyuko has learned.

236
00:13:00,958 --> 00:13:03,541
Pyuko. Sleep Mode.

237
00:13:08,458 --> 00:13:09,375
[shouts]

238
00:13:09,458 --> 00:13:12,000
[PYUKO]
Pyuko wins.

239
00:13:12,083 --> 00:13:14,916
For 108th consecutive time.

240
00:13:15,000 --> 00:13:18,041
[TAMOTSU sighs]
The golden days of humankind

241
00:13:18,125 --> 00:13:20,166
ruling the boards are over!

242
00:13:20,250 --> 00:13:22,583
I hate this.

243
00:13:22,666 --> 00:13:23,875
